<HEADLINE>
<P>
BR'ER NRA IS COZY IN BUSH'S BRIER PATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERNEST B. FURGURSON, Ernest B. Furgurson writes a syndicated column in 
Washington. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Br'er Rabbit is the National Rifle Assn. The brier patch is President Bush's 
new $1.2-billion anti-crime package. 
</P>
<P>
The NRA wailed predictably that the President would violate the Bill of Rights 
and deprive patriotic American voters of their constitutional right to pack the 
firepower of a Marine infantry battalion. Now the arms industry, driving force 
of the NRA, will make even more profits out of the President's proposal. 
</P>
<P>
Much of the package is what its title claims: anti-crime. It includes tougher 
sentencing, more jail cells and hundreds of new federal agents and prosecutors. 
The controversial and sadly laughable part is about controlling deadly weapons. 
</P>
<P>
Four modifiers are necessary to describe the guns that Bush dared suggest 
banning: "certain imported semiautomatic assault" weapons. 
</P>
<P>
That's slicing it pretty thin. And those weapons would be permanently banned 
only if a government review finds that they are not for sporting purposes. 
</P>
<P>
Domestic production and sale of such weapons -- three-fourths of the total -- 
would not be affected. Of course, they fire just as fast and kill just as 
efficiently as the imported models. But the only restriction on them would be 
to ban cartridge magazines holding more than 15 rounds. 
</P>
<P>
That's slicing it even thinner. Bush said that magazines feeding 15-plus rounds 
are "unjustifiably large." Thus, those holding 15 or fewer are justifiably 
large. 
</P>
<P>
The fuss over "semiautomatic assault weapons" has distracted from the serious 
question of gun control. The most emotional control advocates are simply 
ignorant of what the terms mean. The gun lobby is happy to watch a fierce 
debate over this marginal issue while debate over the vast majority of deadly 
weapons is forgotten. 
</P>
<P>
Some advocates have urged a ban on all semiautomatic weapons. That means all 
guns that chamber another round for firing after each trigger pull. The 
familiar Dick Tracy "automatic" and Army Colt .45 "automatic" pistol are 
semiautomatics. So are hunting rifles and shotguns that fire one shot with each 
trigger pull, without manual cocking or feeding. 
</P>
<P>
The great 1989 campaign against "semi-automatic" weapons began with the 
massacre of children in a California schoolyard. As Bush noted, the murderer 
used an AK-47, the Soviet assault rifle with which communist arsenals have 
flooded the world. The AK-47, like the American M-16, can be rendered fully 
automatic, firing bursts with a single trigger pull, and is often used that way 
in combat. 
</P>
<P>
To control all semiautomatics might be a good thing, but that's not what the 
current hullabaloo is about. However, the President did his bit to confuse the 
question further. He decided to define assault weapons as those with magazines 
feeding more than 15 rounds, and to halt their import (but not their 
manufacture here). Yet he spoke of boosting penalties for use of "semiautomatic 
weapons." Does he mean that, or does he mean assault weapons? There would be 
little point in toughening up against criminals who use slide-operated pistols 
but not against those who use revolvers. There also seems little point in 
banning imported weapons but shrugging at identical domestic ones. 
</P>
<P>
Little practical point, that is. Politically, there is a major point: While the 
gun lobby, as a matter of tactics, rises up against all gun controls, its 
special interest is the U.S. arms industry. It won the Administration debate 
leading up to Bush's anti-crime package, as it has won repeatedly against 
congressional arms-control efforts. 
</P>
<P>
The gun lobby argues that any slightest restriction on firearms in any city or 
state is a first step toward destroying the Davy Crockett tradition in America. 
The simplest gun nuts actually believe that. But the more sophisticated know 
better. They are publicly upset today, as if Bush had dealt their business a 
mortal blow instead of a meaningless feather-tap. But they are chortling as 
they shriek. (Try it). 
</P>
<P>
By condemning over-15-round magazines and blessing 15-and-under, Bush has 
created for them a new marketing opportunity. Watch for it in all your 
"outdoor" magazines: the 2-for-1 deal on 15-round banana clips, tailor-made for 
your AK-47, M-16, Uzi, all your favorite sporting rifles. 
</P>
<P>
Remember, guns don't kill people, magazines do. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Obituary 
</P>
