<HEADLINE>
<P>
RECORD RACK: THE GODFATHERS "MORE SONGS ABOUT LOVE AND HATE." EPIC **: ALBUMS 
ARE RATED ON A SCALE OF ONE STAR (POOR) TO FIVE STARS (A CLASSIC). 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DON WALLER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This second effort from the besuited British quintet best-known for the 
roiling, boiling single "Birth, School, Work, Death" (1988) is as bedrock-solid 
as it is ultimately unspectacular. Not a bum track in the bunch, but aside from 
"Walking, Talking Johnny Cash Blues" -- a definite cult classick -- and the 
current single "She Gives Me Love" -- which pretty much packs everything these 
wise guys know into one lashing, slashing hunk of pop aggression -- there's 
naught that memorable either. Still, fans of dour vocals, sour romance, kinda 
Kinks-y, semi-Stonesy, sixtieszoid riffslinging -- (some HAIR-raising guitar 
outros here) can lay their ample heads on this weary bosom and find that the 
heart of rock 'n' roll is still making an offer you can't refuse. DON WALLER 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Recording Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA052189-0075 </DOCNO>
