<HEADLINE>
<P>
A DESPERATE DASH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The level of desperation felt by many illegal immigrants to the United States 
was poignantly captured by Times photographer Don Bartletti last Thursday 
afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
While on an assignment just north of the border, Bartletti saw a man walking in 
a ditch alongside Interstate 805. 
</P>
<P>
Two U. S. Border Patrol vans were nearby, apparently in pursuit. To escape 
arrest, the man bolted onto the freeway into the path of three cars, seemingly 
without looking. 
</P>
<P>
The man narrowly missed being hit, just a few yards north of a sign warning 
motorists to watch for pedestrians -- a sign that may have saved his life. 
</P>
<P>
Dozens of others, especially at night, have not been so lucky in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
Sadly, this scene seems bound to be repeated as long as desperate people, the 
Border Patrol and high-speed traffic mix so dangerously in the South Bay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
