<HEADLINE>
<P>
EVERYONE'S BACK YARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Several supporters of offshore oil drilling have accused their opposition of 
selfishly whining, "Not in my back yard." I agree that there is some element of 
hypocrisy in claiming environmental concern while living the Southern 
California life style. 
</P>
<P>
Yet the Exxon oil spill in Alaska has demonstrated to the whole country that 
Prince William Sound is in fact everybody's back yard. Some of us may not have 
even heard of Prince William Sound before March, but the price we are now 
paying for gasoline proves how close we are to that oil spill. 
</P>
<P>
Locally, though, there is an impact even greater than the price of gasoline. 
Every night we are shown on television what it would be like to have oil slicks 
2 feet thick on our beaches. In our harbors. In the lagoons. In our front 
yards. 
</P>
<P>
I hope everybody in San Diego County car-pools to the workshop scheduled for 1 
to 7 p.m. Monday at Carlsbad's Public Safety Center. Comments from the public 
have been invited. 
</P>
<P>
RUSSELL D. SPENCER 
</P>
<P>
Vista 
</P>
</TEXT>
