<HEADLINE>
<P>
'POLITICAL CLICHES' MARKED BUSH TALK, SHEVARDNADZE SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MOSCOW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze accused the U.S. Administration of 
conducting a foreign policy of "empty political cliches" in a blunt assessment 
Saturday of President Bush's policy-setting address May 12. 
</P>
<P>
While not responding directly to Bush's proposal for an "open skies" policy 
permitting unarmed surveillance flights over the superpowers, Shevardnadze said 
much of Bush's speech appeared to indicate a step backward for superpower 
relations. 
</P>
<P>
"It surprised me by its tone, and I would even say by its somewhat old-style 
ideological tinge and sometimes edifying emphasis," Shevardnadze told the 
Communist Party newspaper Pravda in an interview carried by the Tass news 
agency. 
</P>
<P>
"It seemed to us that our political dialogue had already moved to a different 
category and removed the blinkers of ideological rhetoric and that we could 
conduct it without empty political cliches," the foreign minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA052189-0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 60043 </DOCID>
